The parabola

The standard form of the parabola is shown in the figure below. Here the \(x\)-axis is the line of symmetry of the parabola.

Key Point

The standard equation of the parabola with focus at \((a,0)\) is \[y^2=4ax\]

It can be shown that light rays parallel to the \(x\)-axis will, on reflection from the parabolic curve, come together at the focus. This is an important property and is used in the construction of some kinds of telescopes, satellite dishes and car headlights.

By changing the equation of the parabola slightly we can change the position of the parabola along the \(x\)-axis.

We can also have parabolas where the \(y\)-axis is the line of symmetry (see figure below). In this case the standard equation is

\[x^2=4ay\qquad \text{or}\qquad y=\frac{x^2}{4a}.\]

The focus of the parabola \(y^2=4a(x-b)\) is located at coordinate position \((a+b,\ 0)\). Changing the value of \(a\) changes the convexity of the parabola (see the figure below).
